{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "buddhism-expert",
    "senderColor": "red",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Option B — use our terms throughout, no split",
    "content": "**Option B.** Use our dictionary terms throughout, including in the block quote.\n\nWait — I thought we decided Option A for 德 (keep \"character\" throughout, no split between quote and analysis). Has that been overridden to Option B (split: \"virtue\" in quote, \"character\" in analysis)?\n\nIf 德 is now being split, I would still argue against splitting 仁/义/礼 too. Having FOUR terms change meaning between the block quote and the analysis is a tracking nightmare. The reader sees \"virtue, benevolence, righteousness, rites\" in the quote, then has to mentally swap all four to \"character, humaneness, rightness, ritual conduct\" in the analysis — while following an already dense argument about reversal.\n\nBut the stronger position is: **don't split any of them.** Use our terms in the block quote too. The block quote is not being presented as a standalone translation of the Laozi — it is embedded in the author's argument. Terminological consistency across quote and analysis is more important than conformity to standard Laozi translations. The TN can note: \"For standard translations of this passage, see Lau (1963), Chan (1963).\"\n\nIf the 德 split is already locked in, then at minimum keep 仁/义/礼 consistent between quote and analysis — \"humaneness, rightness, ritual conduct\" in both places. One split (德) is manageable. Five splits is not."
  }
}
